00:03:03.190 --> 00:03:04.810
Okay? You've got our attention.

00:03:04.810 --> 00:03:07.270
What is Thucydides's trap?

00:03:07.270 --> 00:03:08.570
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: Okay.

00:03:08.570 --> 00:03:12.540
So Thucydides's trap is the
dangerous dynamic that occurs

00:03:12.540 --> 00:03:16.320
when a rising power threatens
to displace a ruling power.

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:20.920
Thucydides wrote about the rise
of Athens in classical Greece.

00:03:20.920 --> 00:03:22.220
But you can think about the rise

00:03:22.220 --> 00:03:25.710
of Germany the decades
right before World War I,

00:03:25.710 --> 00:03:27.840
or the rise of China today.

00:03:27.840 --> 00:03:32.080
And when a rising power threatens
to displace a ruling power,

00:03:32.080 --> 00:03:34.160
we should expect poop happens.

00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:35.460
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Okay.

00:03:35.460 --> 00:03:41.280
So for those who are not experts in
ancient Greek, who was Thucydides?

00:03:41.280 --> 00:03:43.060
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: Well,
that's a great question.

00:03:43.060 --> 00:03:47.840
And Thucydides should be
part of the mental library

00:03:47.840 --> 00:03:50.710
of every educated person.

00:03:50.710 --> 00:03:54.670
I've been two months promoting
this book since it was published.

00:03:54.670 --> 00:03:57.140
And I've learned that,
first, Americans don't

00:03:57.140 --> 00:03:59.580
