00:04:49.130 --> 00:04:52.490
And if every page doesn't
make your heart go pitter-pat,

00:04:52.490 --> 00:04:53.790
check your pulse.

00:04:53.790 --> 00:04:55.090
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: All right.

00:04:55.090 --> 00:04:56.390
Well, let's talk about this.

00:04:56.390 --> 00:04:57.690
So what he did is he wrote a
book on the Peloponnesian War,

00:04:57.690 --> 00:05:02.080
which was a war between Sparta,
which was the dominant power

00:05:02.080 --> 00:05:06.280
in the Peloponnesians, and then
Athens, which was the rising power.

00:05:06.280 --> 00:05:09.380
So under Thucydides's
trap, the trap being

00:05:09.380 --> 00:05:14.070
that the rising power ultimately
might get the feeling it should

00:05:14.070 --> 00:05:19.110
attack the larger power,
the more traditional power,

00:05:19.110 --> 00:05:20.410
who attacked there?

00:05:20.410 --> 00:05:21.930
Did Athens attack Sparta?

00:05:21.930 --> 00:05:23.230
Is that what happened?

00:05:23.230 --> 00:05:24.530
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: Well,
that's a great question,

00:05:24.530 --> 00:05:29.450
because Thucydides's main idea
was that you have this dynamic.

00:05:29.450 --> 00:05:31.740
I'm the ruling power.

00:05:31.740 --> 00:05:33.220
You're the rising power.

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:36.010
The rising power is
thinking, "I'm bigger.

00:05:36.010 --> 00:05:37.310
I'm stronger.

00:05:37.310 --> 00:05:38.610
I deserve more say.

00:05:38.610 --> 00:05:40.020
I deserve more sway.

00:05:40.020 --> 00:05:43.410
The current arrangements don't
take account of my interests."

00:05:43.410 --> 00:05:46.120
And the ruling power thinks,
"This other [inaudible] is trying

00:05:46.120 --> 00:05:50.300 position:56%
to upset the status quo that's
provided the environment that's been

00:05:50.300 --> 00:05:52.640
good for everybody,
especially for you.

00:05:52.640 --> 00:05:53.940
How did you grow up?"

00:05:53.940 --> 00:05:57.510
So in that environment,
in some cases in the cases

00:05:57.510 --> 00:06:00.570
that I've studied, a
rising power decides, "Well,

00:06:00.570 --> 00:06:02.770
I'll fight the ruling
power," or the ruling power,

00:06:02.770 --> 00:06:04.070
"I'll fight the rising power."

00:06:04.070 --> 00:06:05.370
But that's not Thucydides's story.

00:06:05.370 --> 00:06:10.660
Thucydides's story is that in
this dynamic both protagonists are

00:06:10.660 --> 00:06:13.500
vulnerable to the action
of third parties.

00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:17.140
So in Thucydides's story
you've got a rise of Athens,

00:06:17.140 --> 00:06:22.480 position:56%
the fear in Sparta, and then
Corinth, which is an ally of Sparta,

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:24.370
gets into a tangle with Corcyra.

00:06:24.370 --> 00:06:29.320
And they drag Athens and Sparta
into a war neither of them wanted.

00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:30.620
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Okay.

00:06:30.620 --> 00:06:31.920
But in the end Athens
attacked Sparta?

00:06:31.920 --> 00:06:35.140
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: Well,
again, it becomes complicated.

00:06:35.140 --> 00:06:37.960
They get dragged in.

00:06:37.960 --> 00:06:43.110
The Spartans began
violating the terms,--

00:06:43.110 --> 00:06:44.410
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Okay.

00:06:44.410 --> 00:06:45.710
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: The
Athenians vote for war.

00:06:45.710 --> 00:06:47.010
And then there's about six months

00:06:47.010 --> 00:06:48.660
in which the war doesn't
actually happen,

00:06:48.660 --> 00:06:50.970
where they could have
resolved the war even then.

00:06:50.970 --> 00:06:52.270
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Okay.

00:06:52.270 --> 00:06:53.570
All right.

00:06:53.570 --> 00:06:54.870
So at Harvard, the Kennedy School,
you started something called

00:06:54.870 --> 00:06:58.510
"Thucydides's Trap
Project," which said, "Okay.

00:06:58.510 --> 00:07:02.270
If Athens and Sparta had this
problem, and they went to war,

00:07:02.270 --> 00:07:05.140
let's see how many cases
in the ensuing 2,000 years

00:07:05.140 --> 00:07:09.990
or so there were similar situations
where a rising power got trapped

00:07:09.990 --> 00:07:13.400
into attacking a more
dominant power."

00:07:13.400 --> 00:07:15.530
So how many instances were there?

00:07:15.530 --> 00:07:18.580
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: Well, so we've
only looked at the last 500 years.

00:07:18.580 --> 00:07:19.880
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Okay.

00:07:19.880 --> 00:07:21.420
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: So just
the most recent 500 years,

00:07:21.420 --> 00:07:24.450
starting with the end
of the 15th century--

00:07:24.450 --> 00:07:25.750
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: All right.

00:07:25.750 --> 00:07:27.050
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison:
Up until currently.

00:07:27.050 --> 00:07:31.270
We found 16 cases, 1, 6, in
which a rising power threatens

00:07:31.270 --> 00:07:33.050
to displace a ruling power.

00:07:33.050 --> 00:07:35.380
Twelve of them ended in war.

00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:37.150
Four of them in not war.

00:07:37.150 --> 00:07:38.450
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Okay.

00:07:38.450 --> 00:07:41.370
So to avoid the Thucydides's
trap, you have to figure

00:07:41.370 --> 00:07:45.540
out what the four did that avoided
the war, and what the twelve did

00:07:45.540 --> 00:07:46.890
that didn't avoid the war.

00:07:46.890 --> 00:07:49.560
Okay. So let's go through
some examples through history.

00:07:49.560 --> 00:07:53.270
So let's take an example
where a war was not avoided.

00:07:53.270 --> 00:08:00.390 position:56%
A rising power in the west was Japan
in the late 1930s and early 1940s.

00:08:00.390 --> 00:08:04.600 position:56%
The United States is the dominant
power in the Pacific to some extent.

00:08:04.600 --> 00:08:06.520
So how did that come about?

00:08:06.520 --> 00:08:09.470
Did Japan feel the United States
didn't take them seriously enough?

00:08:09.470 --> 00:08:11.210
The United States didn't
know how to treat Japan?

00:08:11.210 --> 00:08:12.700
What happened there?

00:08:12.700 --> 00:08:15.390
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: Well,
it's a great question.

00:08:15.390 --> 00:08:16.690
And it's a long story.

00:08:16.690 --> 00:08:19.310
But I'll just try to do
the capsule in the book.

00:08:19.310 --> 00:08:23.520
In the appendix I give a little
capsule histories of each of these.

00:08:23.520 --> 00:08:31.770
So basically about the turn of the
century, maybe just the beginning,

00:08:31.770 --> 00:08:36.070
Japan starts rising and
getting bigger and stronger.

00:08:36.070 --> 00:08:41.280
All of Asia has been
colonized by everybody else.

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:44.990
The U.S. establishes something
called an open-door policy

00:08:44.990 --> 00:08:48.020
in which it says everything's
going to stay the way things are.

00:08:48.020 --> 00:08:52.380
But the Japanese are feeling their
cut out of guaranteed resources

00:08:52.380 --> 00:08:54.710
as their economy gets
bigger and stronger.

00:08:54.710 --> 00:08:57.120 position:56%
So they begin to be more aggressive.

00:08:57.120 --> 00:08:59.770
They act against China.

00:08:59.770 --> 00:09:01.740
They are aggressive
against Indonesia.

00:09:01.740 --> 00:09:04.580
The U.S. says to them,
"Absolutely not.

00:09:04.580 --> 00:09:07.840
Stop." But first we do
a trade war with them.

00:09:07.840 --> 00:09:11.300
Then we do an embargo
on their shipments.

00:09:11.300 --> 00:09:14.050
Then we do an oil embargo.

00:09:14.050 --> 00:09:17.230
And not realizing and
not understanding

00:09:17.230 --> 00:09:19.630
that from the Japanese
point of view this looked

00:09:19.630 --> 00:09:21.640 position:56%
like we were simply strangling them.

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:23.440
And we were to the point of where

00:09:23.440 --> 00:09:26.680
in the Japanese calculation
they could either be strangled

00:09:26.680 --> 00:09:30.480
by the U.S. immediately,
or they could take a chance

00:09:30.480 --> 00:09:33.730
on attacking the U.S. at
Pearl Harbor, as they did.

00:09:33.730 --> 00:09:35.030
And, so, they chose to attack.

00:09:35.030 --> 00:09:36.330
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Okay.

00:09:36.330 --> 00:09:37.630
So that's what happened there.

00:09:37.630 --> 00:09:38.930
The Thucydides's trap
could not be avoided.

00:09:38.930 --> 00:09:40.230
Let's take another example.

00:09:40.230 --> 00:09:42.760
In the early part of the
20th century in Europe,

00:09:42.760 --> 00:09:44.900
Germany was a rising power.

00:09:44.900 --> 00:09:47.500
And while we know Germany
is a powerful country then,

00:09:47.500 --> 00:09:49.110
it was really coming
together as a country,

00:09:49.110 --> 00:09:52.490
because it was being put together,
the dominant power was England.

00:09:52.490 --> 00:09:55.090
So how did Germany look at England?

00:09:55.090 --> 00:09:58.610
And how did they not avoid that
the Thucydides's trap there?

00:09:58.610 --> 00:09:59.910
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: Well, again,

00:09:59.910 --> 00:10:03.110
I have a chapter on
"The Road to 1914."

00:10:03.110 --> 00:10:08.260
And I would say this is the
most eerie in similarity

00:10:08.260 --> 00:10:10.830
