which was completely bizarre,

00:11:13.600 --> 00:11:17.650
[inaudible] the Archduke, who
was the successor to the throne

00:11:17.650 --> 00:11:22.990
in Vienna, was assassinated in
Sarajevo by a Serbian terrorist.

00:11:22.990 --> 00:11:25.670
So it would have been an
inconsequential event normally.

00:11:25.670 --> 00:11:29.170
But that end up to serve as
a trigger to a set of actions

00:11:29.170 --> 00:11:32.790
and reactions, by the end of
which all the parties were at war.

00:11:32.790 --> 00:11:34.090
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: All right.

00:11:34.090 --> 00:11:36.110
So in the case of World
War II and World War I,

00:11:36.110 --> 00:11:38.600
the Thucydides's trap
was not avoided.

00:11:38.600 --> 00:11:41.180
Let's take a case where
it was avoided.

00:11:41.180 --> 00:11:46.030
In the lifetime of many people
here it was thought, by some of us,

00:11:46.030 --> 00:11:47.520
that maybe the United States

00:11:47.520 --> 00:11:50.710
and the then Soviet Union
could not avoid war.

00:11:50.710 --> 00:11:53.380
We were the two dominant
post-World War II powers.

00:11:53.380 --> 00:11:56.370
But we actually ended the
Cold War without any Hot War.

00:11:56.370 --> 00:11:59.120
How did we actually
avoid the Hot War?

00:11:59.120 --> 00:12:02.080 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: Well, again, this
