&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: It's a real
serious structural stress.

00:34:07.520 --> 00:34:08.820
Then they say, "Well,
okay, if we were trying

00:34:08.820 --> 00:34:12.170
to avoid Thucydides's trap, or
escape, what do we have to do?"

00:34:12.170 --> 00:34:13.730
And I go through my suggestions,

00:34:13.730 --> 00:34:16.350
[inaudible] you would
wish [inaudible] would be

00:34:16.350 --> 00:34:20.240
that the two governments, Xi
and Trump, would appoint two

00:34:20.240 --> 00:34:23.480
or three people each who they
trusted, and say, "You folks sit

00:34:23.480 --> 00:34:29.090
down and be imaginative, not just
within the box, very imaginative.

00:34:29.090 --> 00:34:31.820
And ask first how are
the ways that parties

00:34:31.820 --> 00:34:35.670
like Kim Jong-un could drag
us into a war we don't want?

00:34:35.670 --> 00:34:36.970
Let's be clear.

00:34:36.970 --> 00:34:39.390
How could this happen, and what
do we have to do to prevent that?"

00:34:39.390 --> 00:34:41.070
So that part would be pretty easy.

00:34:41.070 --> 00:34:48.090
Then, secondly, how do we adapt
and adjust in this relationship,

00:34:48.090 --> 00:34:50.780
which is going to be painful, in
which we're going to each have

00:34:50.780 --> 00:34:53.000
to do things different
than we have been--

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:54.300
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Right.

00:34:54.300 --> 00:34:55.600
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: Doing before?

00:34:55.600 --> 00:34:56.900
And in that what you would
like is to distinguish

00:34:56.900 --> 00:35:00.350
between vital national
interests for each party,

00:35:00.350 --> 00:35:02.070
and things that are just vested.

00:35:02.070 --> 00:35:04.940
So some of the things that the
U.S. is doing we've been doing

00:35:04.940 --> 00:35:06.240
for 70 years.

00:35:06.240 --> 00:35:08.070
But we don't have to
be doing forever.

00:35:08.070 --> 00:35:12.820
I would say it's now my personal
view the U.S. interests in who owns

00:35:12.820 --> 00:35:17.010
which island in the South
China Sea is pretty limited.

00:35:17.010 --> 00:35:20.510
I would like to see us
fight over who the Paracels

00:35:20.510 --> 00:35:24.160
or the Scarborough
Shoals, or some island

00:35:24.160 --> 00:35:26.920
that the Chinese built
in the South China Sea.

00:35:26.920 --> 00:35:30.710
Well, then do you mean you would be
willing to compromise in some way?

00:35:30.710 --> 00:35:34.530
I would say in the Cold War we
compromised in a lot of ways.

00:35:34.530 --> 00:35:37.880
The captive nations of
Eastern Europe stayed captive

00:35:37.880 --> 00:35:39.180
for four decades.

00:35:39.180 --> 00:35:41.550 position:56%
We didn't go fight to liberate them.

00:35:41.550 --> 00:35:43.740
We dealt with this over
a longer period of time.

00:35:43.740 --> 00:35:47.930
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: So today
as you look at Thucydides's trap

00:35:47.930 --> 00:35:50.660
in the history, and you look
at the Chinese leadership,

00:35:50.660 --> 00:35:53.890
you look at the American
leadership, how likely in your view

00:35:53.890 --> 00:35:57.800
over the next five, ten or 15
or 20 years do you think it is

00:35:57.800 --> 00:36:00.430
that the United States
and China will be unable

00:36:00.430 --> 00:36:03.900
to avoid this Thucydides's trap?

00:36:03.900 --> 00:36:06.650
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: That's
an extremely good question.

00:36:06.650 --> 00:36:09.000
That's a hard question.

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:15.520
In the book I argue I do believe
that history as usual, I'm sorry,

00:36:15.520 --> 00:36:17.050
[inaudible], business as usual.

00:36:17.050 --> 00:36:20.060
If we just do business
as usual in the U.S.

00:36:20.060 --> 00:36:23.550
/Chinese relations we'll
get history as usual.

00:36:23.550 --> 00:36:24.850
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Okay.

00:36:24.850 --> 00:36:26.150
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: And history
as usual is pretty catastrophic.

00:36:26.150 --> 00:36:30.310
But, as I argue in the book
also, as Santiana taught us,

00:36:30.310 --> 00:36:35.660
only if we refuse to study history
