00:36:35.660 --> 00:36:40.470
So, now, can I imagine the U.S.
government being as imaginative

00:36:40.470 --> 00:36:43.090
as people were in inventing
the Cold War strategy?

00:36:43.090 --> 00:36:45.520
I can. I mean we already
did this once.

00:36:45.520 --> 00:36:48.720
Could I imagine China being
inventive, especially since,

00:36:48.720 --> 00:36:51.370
as you say, they've
got a long horizon?

00:36:51.370 --> 00:36:54.430
So they prepared to take issues
and put them on the shelf

00:36:54.430 --> 00:36:56.110
for a long period of time.

00:36:56.110 --> 00:37:01.620
But I would say if the performance
for the next 20 years was,

00:37:01.620 --> 00:37:06.980
if it's no different than the
performance in the last 20 years,

00:37:06.980 --> 00:37:08.580
then I would say the likelihood

00:37:08.580 --> 00:37:14.010
of conflict is significant,
maybe 40%, yeah.

00:37:14.010 --> 00:37:15.310
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
But conflict--

00:37:15.310 --> 00:37:16.610
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: War.

00:37:16.610 --> 00:37:17.910
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
Non-nuclear--

00:37:17.910 --> 00:37:19.210
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: War.

00:37:19.210 --> 00:37:20.510
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
Non-nuclear [inaudible].

00:37:20.510 --> 00:37:22.350
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: Well,
I hope non-nuclear.

00:37:22.350 --> 00:37:26.930
But part of the reason why
in the Cold War the U.S.

00:37:26.930 --> 00:37:31.000
and the Soviet Union, which
became to be so cautious

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:36.230
about having a non-nuclear war
where we're killing each other,

00:37:36.230 --> 00:37:39.280
is that it's not clear
why it doesn't escalate.

00:37:39.280 --> 00:37:43.050
And, as I point out in the
book, now that you have cyber

00:37:43.050 --> 00:37:50.050
as another lubricant, as well as
the normal ways in which you can,

00:37:50.050 --> 00:37:52.310
once you have a war
going the question is,

00:37:52.310 --> 00:37:54.200
"Why should I lose at this level--

00:37:54.200 --> 00:37:55.500
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Right.

00:37:55.500 --> 00:37:56.810
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: Rather
than move up just a level?"

00:37:56.810 --> 00:38:00.360
And Putin has already
introduced into the conversation,

00:38:00.360 --> 00:38:03.620
and the Chinese have been
looking at this very carefully,

00:38:03.620 --> 00:38:06.070
the notion that, well,
but if I'm losing

00:38:06.070 --> 00:38:10.690
at the conventional level I can
just use a tactical nuclear weapon,

00:38:10.690 --> 00:38:13.110
just a limited use
of a nuclear weapon.

00:38:13.110 --> 00:38:15.190
And while you and I
would say, "Yikes!

00:38:15.190 --> 00:38:16.580
That sounds crazy."

00:38:16.580 --> 00:38:19.890
That was actually what we
thought of doing in the Cold War

00:38:19.890 --> 00:38:22.380
when we thought we had
only a few divisions,

00:38:22.380 --> 00:38:24.720
and the Soviet Union
had a lot of divisions.

00:38:24.720 --> 00:38:28.660
So I would say stay out
of a conventional war,

00:38:28.660 --> 00:38:32.790
because don't have any
comfort or confidence

00:38:32.790 --> 00:38:34.590
that it wouldn't escalate
to something much worse.

00:38:34.590 --> 00:38:35.900
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Now
