been in the news a lot lately,

00:38:38.500 --> 00:38:42.840
so it's not quite in your book, but
your own assessment as a scholar

00:38:42.840 --> 00:38:45.750
in this area and somebody
who studied this area, China,

00:38:45.750 --> 00:38:47.560
North Korea, United States,

00:38:47.560 --> 00:38:51.990
why is it that the Chinese can't
have more influence on North Korea,

00:38:51.990 --> 00:38:56.110
and get Kim Jong-un
to seem more rational?

00:38:56.110 --> 00:38:57.410
What's the reason?

00:38:57.410 --> 00:38:58.710
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison:
That's a great question.

00:38:58.710 --> 00:39:01.380
And I think he hasn't been,

00:39:01.380 --> 00:39:06.010
he and they haven't been
sufficiently motivated to do so.

00:39:06.010 --> 00:39:10.110
China controls the oil
lifeline to North Korea.

00:39:10.110 --> 00:39:15.310
Ninety percent of all oil that
fuels the trucks and the planes

00:39:15.310 --> 00:39:19.400 position:56%
for the military, as well as the
cars for the leadership when they go

00:39:19.400 --> 00:39:22.960
to their country houses on
the weekend, comes from China.

00:39:22.960 --> 00:39:25.560
So if it squeezed that lifeline,

00:39:25.560 --> 00:39:28.200
it could have a huge
impact on North Korea.

00:39:28.200 --> 00:39:29.500
But,--

00:39:29.500 --> 00:39:30.800
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
Why can't they do it?

00:39:30.800 --> 00:39:32.100
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: Well, put
it in a, if you put it back

00:39:32.100 --> 00:39:36.010
into the Thucydides in context,
the Chinese when they look

00:39:36.010 --> 00:39:39.840
at this situation, as one said
to me, "Look, there's no problem

00:39:39.840 --> 00:39:45.490
in the Korean Peninsula that
wouldn't be solved if you left.

00:39:45.490 --> 00:39:47.960
The problem is you're there."

00:39:47.960 --> 00:39:52.270
I mean if the U.S. were not
on the Korean Peninsula,

00:39:52.270 --> 00:39:55.150
you would have a unified Korea.

00:39:55.150 --> 00:39:58.140
It would be a tributary
state of China.

00:39:58.140 --> 00:40:00.470
They would allow it to
have nuclear weapons.

00:40:00.470 --> 00:40:03.360
So this is, and I said to
them, "Well, wait a minute.

00:40:03.360 --> 00:40:06.370
I can understand why
you might think that.

00:40:06.370 --> 00:40:09.800
But let me tell you about my
history, how we got there.

00:40:09.800 --> 00:40:11.380
We didn't volunteer to come there.

00:40:11.380 --> 00:40:14.050
We came there because
your ally attacked them."

00:40:14.050 --> 00:40:16.070
The story I told before.

00:40:16.070 --> 00:40:20.090
So the North Korean as a
situation is extremely dangerous,

00:40:20.090 --> 00:40:25.990
because it's an overlay on
this fundamental dynamic.

00:40:25.990 --> 00:40:31.070
And I think from Xi's
point of view, if you look,

00:40:31.070 --> 00:40:35.830
he saw they're almost working
as hard to sanction South Korea

00:40:35.830 --> 00:40:39.880
for its deployment of
THAAD, of missile defenses.

00:40:39.880 --> 00:40:44.140
So look and see what's happening
to Hyundai or Samsung in China,

00:40:44.140 --> 00:40:47.440
or what's happening to
Chinese visits to South Korea.

00:40:47.440 --> 00:40:51.560
So they see this in terms of
a much more complex dynamic.

00:40:51.560 --> 00:40:53.100
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
Now we avoided a Hot War

00:40:53.100 --> 00:40:55.100
with the Soviet Union
you pointed out,

00:40:55.100 --> 00:40:59.440
because a containment approach
