00:42:48.590 --> 00:42:49.890
But--

00:42:49.890 --> 00:42:51.190
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: George Kennan.

00:42:51.190 --> 00:42:52.490
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: In
the two minutes we have left,

00:42:52.490 --> 00:42:53.790
I would like you to
do this in two minutes

00:42:53.790 --> 00:42:55.090
in a slightly different context.

00:42:55.090 --> 00:42:58.880 position:56%
You are the leading expert, academic
expert on the Cuban Missile Crisis.

00:42:58.880 --> 00:43:02.950
So what happened there that
avoided a confrontation?

00:43:02.950 --> 00:43:05.930
What was the brilliance of
President Kennedy or his advisors?

00:43:05.930 --> 00:43:09.890
How did we avoid it, in that case,
going to a nuclear confrontation?

00:43:09.890 --> 00:43:12.380
And what lesson would you
take away that you would give

00:43:12.380 --> 00:43:14.320
to the current administration
they should take

00:43:14.320 --> 00:43:16.570
from the Cuban Missile
Crisis in two minutes?

00:43:16.570 --> 00:43:17.870
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: Okay.

00:43:17.870 --> 00:43:20.260
So the Cuban Missile
Crisis, for those of you

00:43:20.260 --> 00:43:24.110
who missed it, was in 1962.

00:43:24.110 --> 00:43:28.140
Okay? And it's the most dangerous
moment in recorded history.

00:43:28.140 --> 00:43:30.940
So the U.S. discovered
the Soviet Union trying

00:43:30.940 --> 00:43:33.400
to place nuclear-tipped
missiles in Cuba.

00:43:33.400 --> 00:43:35.430
Kennedy determined this
is not going to stand.

00:43:35.430 --> 00:43:37.580
We're not going to
allow this to happen.

00:43:37.580 --> 00:43:40.520
And actually took a
course of action,

00:43:40.520 --> 00:43:44.230
which he thought had a
one-in-three chance of nuclear war,

00:43:44.230 --> 00:43:48.940
to prevent the Soviet Union from
having nuclear-tipped missiles

00:43:48.940 --> 00:43:51.960
in Cuba, even though they already
had nuclear-tipped missiles

00:43:51.960 --> 00:43:53.860
in the Soviet Union
that could kill us.

00:43:53.860 --> 00:43:55.850
So that's a long complicated story.

00:43:55.850 --> 00:43:58.620
In any case, we started
it with a blockade.

00:43:58.620 --> 00:44:01.240
So no more shipments to Cuba.

00:44:01.240 --> 00:44:04.840
And then by the end of the second
week, all this was condensed

00:44:04.840 --> 00:44:11.910 position:56%
in 13 days, Kennedy gave to the
Soviet Union a very strange cocktail

00:44:11.910 --> 00:44:14.290
to Khrushchev, communicated
to him privately.

00:44:14.290 --> 00:44:16.510
First, a public demand.

00:44:16.510 --> 00:44:18.530
The missiles have to be withdrawn.

00:44:18.530 --> 00:44:23.720
Secondly, a private ultimatum
that if this doesn't happen in 24

00:44:23.720 --> 00:44:27.190
or 48 hours, I'm going
to attack these missiles.

00:44:27.190 --> 00:44:32.030
And, thirdly, a secret
sweetener that said the missiles

00:44:32.030 --> 00:44:35.870
that we have deployed in Turkey,
that you're so concerned about,

00:44:35.870 --> 00:44:37.980
I'm not going to have
any quid pro quo.

00:44:37.980 --> 00:44:41.740
But I'm telling you if we resolve
the Cuban issue in six months,

00:44:41.740 --> 00:44:43.450
those missiles will be gone.

00:44:43.450 --> 00:44:45.540
So Kennedy drew from this,

00:44:45.540 --> 00:44:49.620 position:56%
what he thought was the big takeaway
going forward, that when you get it

00:44:49.620 --> 00:44:55.450
to basically eyeball-to-eyeball,
don't give your adversary a choice

00:44:55.450 --> 00:44:58.290
between humiliation and war.

00:44:58.290 --> 00:44:59.590
Find some other--

00:44:59.590 --> 00:45:00.890
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Okay.

00:45:00.890 --> 00:45:02.190
&gt;&gt; Graham Allison: Option.

00:45:02.190 --> 00:45:04.240 position:56%
And I would hope that in this
current situation, as we look at it,

00:45:04.240 --> 00:45:07.700
we would end up finding
something equally imaginative.

00:45:07.700 --> 00:45:09.000
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: All right.

